SIMPLE: juvenile
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Juvenile
<hw>Ju"ve*nile</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>juvenilis</ets>, from <ets>juvenis</ets> young; akin to E.
<ets>young</ets>: cf. F. <ets>juv⟦eacute⟧nile</ets>,
<ets>juv⟦eacute⟧nil</ets>. See <er>Young</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Young; youthful; <as>as, a <ex>juvenile</ex>
appearance</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>juvenile</xex> exercitation.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to youth; <as>as, <ex>juvenile</ex>
sports</as>.</def></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characteristic of children; immature; childish;
puerile; infantile; <as>as, a <ex>juvenile</ex> temper
tantrum</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Puerile; boyish; childish. See
<er>Youthful</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Juvenile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Juvenile
<hw>Ju"ve*nile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A young person or youth; -- used
sportively or familiarly.</def> <rj><au>C. Bront⟦eacute⟧.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>juvenile delinquent</ent>⟦br⟧
